  <content>
    <title>Rails Patterns (Service Objects)</title>
    <summary>Rails service object pattern: extract multi-step business workflows from fat controllers into app/services/BoundedContext/ActionService classes with a single call method that returns a ServiceResult (success/failure).</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Rails controllers balloon when they own database writes, mailer calls, audit logging, and job enqueuing. ActiveRecord callbacks create unmaintainable side-effect chains. Service objects enforce a single responsibility, make transaction boundaries explicit, and let RSpec test business logic in isolation without loading the full HTTP stack.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Controllers that have grown past ~100 lines and need workflow extraction</item>
        <item>Multi-step business operations (signup, checkout, refund) that span multiple models in one transaction</item>
        <item>Replacing fat-model callbacks when side effects have become unmanageable</item>
        <item>Standardizing controller response shapes: every action maps `ServiceResult` → HTTP status</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Trivial CRUD where a `before_action` + `model.save` already does the job — service objects add indirection without value</item>
        <item>Pure data-access logic — that belongs in Query Objects or scopes, not services</item>
        <item>One-off rake tasks or scripts — plain Ruby objects without the result wrapper are fine</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="service-object-structure">
      <rule>
        <statement>Each service class has exactly one public method: call. If you need a second public method, extract a new service.</statement>
        <rationale>A single call entry point makes the service's contract explicit and keeps RSpec tests focused on one responsibility.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Use keyword arguments in initialize (params:, current_user:). Avoid positional arguments.</statement>
        <rationale>Keyword args are self-documenting, make mocking explicit, and prevent argument order mistakes when a service gains parameters.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Services must be free of HTTP/Rails concerns. They accept plain Ruby hashes or value objects; the controller maps ServiceResult to HTTP status codes.</statement>
        <rationale>HTTP concerns in services prevent unit testing without loading Rails routing or request objects.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Namespace services by bounded context (Users::CreateService, Billing::RefundService), not by HTTP verb. Never name by REST action.</statement>
        <rationale>Context namespacing scales to complex domains. HTTP-verb naming (PostsCreateService) couples the domain model to the HTTP layer.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="service-result-contract">
      <rule>
        <statement>Every service's call method returns a ServiceResult with success?, failure?, data, and errors. Never return raw ActiveRecord objects or raise domain exceptions directly to the controller.</statement>
        <rationale>A single return type makes controller code uniform and prevents dual error paths (exception vs failure result) from diverging.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <reference path="templates/service_result.rb">ServiceResult value object implementation</reference>
    </section>
    <section name="transaction-boundaries">
      <rule>
        <statement>Wrap multi-step writes (save + mailer + job + audit) in ActiveRecord::Base.transaction. Lock the transaction to a single aggregate to avoid distributed-transaction bugs.</statement>
        <rationale>Without a transaction, a mailer exception after user.save! leaves the user created but no email queued — silent inconsistency.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Catch ActiveRecord::RecordInvalid inside the transaction block, not outside. Return ServiceResult.failure with the validation errors.</statement>
        <rationale>Catching outside the transaction after the rescue block may miss partial writes. RecordInvalid rolls back the transaction automatically.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="service-implementation">
      <example type="good" title="Users::CreateService with transaction and deliver_later">
        <code lang="ruby"><![CDATA[
module Users
  class CreateService
    def initialize(params:, current_user: nil)
      @params = params
      @current_user = current_user
    end

    def call
      user = User.new(user_params)
      ActiveRecord::Base.transaction do
        user.save!
        UserMailer.welcome(user).deliver_later
        AuditLog.create!(
          action: 'user.created',
          resource: user,
          actor: @current_user
        )
      end
      ServiceResult.success(user)
    rescue ActiveRecord::RecordInvalid => e
      ServiceResult.failure(e.record.errors.full_messages)
    end

    private

    def user_params
      @params.slice(:name, :email, :password)
    end
  end
end
        ]]></code>
        <note>Service accepts plain hash, not ActionController::Parameters. Mailer uses deliver_later. Transaction wraps save + audit.</note>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="controller-wiring">
      <example type="good" title="Controller mapping ServiceResult to HTTP response">
        <code lang="ruby"><![CDATA[
module Api
  module V1
    class UsersController < ApplicationController
      def create
        result = Users::CreateService.new(
          params: user_params,
          current_user: current_user
        ).call

        if result.success?
          render json: UserSerializer.new(result.data), status: :created
        else
          render json: { errors: result.errors }, status: :unprocessable_entity
        end
      end

      private

      def user_params
        params.require(:user).permit(:name, :email, :password)
      end
    end
  end
end
        ]]></code>
        <note>Controller only maps ServiceResult to HTTP shape. user_params is permitted before passing to service.</note>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Service has multiple public methods (call, create, update) or no call method at all.</description>
        <reason>Breaks single-responsibility; unclear which method is the entry point; harder to compose with organizers. A service is a command object with exactly one entry point.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>rescue StandardError inside the service, swallowing all exceptions into ServiceResult.failure.</description>
        <reason>Hides real bugs (NoMethodError, TypeError) as domain failures. Only catch documented domain exceptions like ActiveRecord::RecordInvalid or custom exceptions.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Service returns raw ActiveRecord object on success, exception on failure — two divergent paths.</description>
        <reason>Controllers must handle both paths differently; ServiceResult enforces a uniform interface.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Services reference params.require(...) or params.permit(...) from the controller. The service couples to Rails ActionController::Parameters.</description>
        <reason>Couples the service to Rails and prevents unit testing without mocking params. Services accept already-permitted plain hashes from the controller, not ActionController::Parameters.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Services call deliver_now or perform_now for mailer/job dispatch, causing service specs to send real emails or run jobs synchronously.</description>
        <reason>Synchronous dispatch makes tests slow, side-effect-prone, and brittle. Always use deliver_later / perform_later so the mailer/job is enqueued, not executed immediately.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="agentic-workflow-and-best-practices">
      <p>Treat a Rails service as a unit of work with a single public call method. A subagent should generate the service, the matching ServiceResult / Dry-Monads return type, the controller wiring, and an RSpec request + service spec in one pass. For larger refactors (extracting from a fat controller), use a planner subagent to map controller actions to services first, then a code subagent per service. Always require the diff include the spec file alongside the service. Quality gates: bundle exec rspec, bundle exec rubocop.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Use keyword args (params:, current_user:) for explicitness; positional args become hard to mock. Keep services free of HTTP/Rails concerns; the controller maps ServiceResult to HTTP status codes.</statement>
        <rationale>Self-documenting, safe from argument-order mistakes. Separating HTTP from domain logic keeps services unit-testable.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>For multi-step workflows, prefer composing small services via an Organizer rather than one 400-line service. Lock ActiveRecord::Base.transaction blocks to a single aggregate to avoid distributed-transaction bugs.</statement>
        <rationale>Small, focused services are easier to test and reuse. Organizers (Interactor pattern) chain services together. Transactions on a single aggregate maintain ACID guarantees.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Human-in-loop checkpoint: review namespace/folder choice (app/services/users/ vs. app/operations/users/) before generation — renaming after the fact is painful due to constant autoload paths.</statement>
        <rationale>Different Rails teams use different conventions; pin it in the project's AGENTS.md ahead of time.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/service_result.rb" purpose="ServiceResult value object with success/failure constructors"/>
      <template path="templates/spec-skeleton.rb" purpose="RSpec request + service spec template covering success, validation failure, DB rollback"/>
    </templates>
